{
  "text": "The above studies all suggest that AMPK activation can decrease \u2423Syn and ameliorate the deficits caused by its aggregation. However, the relationship between AMPK and \u2423Syn is not straightforward. Some studies have noted that \u2423Syn decreases AMPK phosphorylation at Thr172 [CITATION_1] , while others have observed that \u2423Syn increases it [CITATION_2] . One possible explanation for these contradictory findings is that \u2423Syn and phosphorylated \u2423Syn differentially affect AMPK. Under normal physiological conditions, \u2423Syn is mostly unphosphorylated. However, in PD \u2423Syn becomes increasingly phosphorylated at serine 129 (pS129), and over 90% of \u2423Syn within Lewy bodies is phosphorylated [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Unphosphorylated \u2423Syn activates the phosphatase PP2A, which promotes the dephosphorylation of both \u2423Syn and AMPK, whereas pS129-\u2423Syn inhibits PP2A [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Furthermore, pS129-\u2423Syn was found to sequester PIKE-L, an inhibitor of AMPK, leading to increased AMPK activity in mice and in SH-SY5Y cells overexpressing \u2423Syn [CITATION_7] . Thus, unphosphorylated \u2423Syn may inhibit AMPK function through PP2A, but as \u2423Syn becomes increasingly phosphorylated this inhibition declines and other AMPK regulating proteins become inhibited, leading to increased AMPK activity [CITATION_8] . Yet increased AMPK in these conditions may not necessarily correspond with normal physiological AMPK activation. There is evidence that AMPK is highly dysregulated in cultured neurons overexpressing \u2423Syn and in human cells with Lewy body pathology, with AMPK accumulating with \u2423Syn outside the nucleus or around the rim of Lewy bodies [CITATION_9] . Increasing AMPK activity further in this case may be detrimental to both cell survival and \u2423Syn clearance. In mouse primary neuronal cultures, overexpression of \u2423Syn or treatment with lactate increased pS129-\u2423Syn and AMPK activity (as measured by pThr172). Overexpression of AMPK-DN or AMPK knockdown prevented lactate induced increases in pS129 and total \u2423Syn and ameliorated the decreased neurite length in cells overexpressing \u2423Syn or treated with lactate. Conversely, AMPK-CA expression increased \u2423Syn, decreased neurite length, and impaired \u2423Syn turnover in 3D5 cells [CITATION_10] .",
